          "id": "sg-l03-c1",
          "title": "What Exactly Is a Gene? The Immortal Coil",
          "content": "A chromosome is like a long, twisty ladder made of DNA. When living things reproduce, this ladder gets mixed up in a fun way called crossing-over. Imagine two friends swapping pieces of their favorite stickers; that's similar to what happens with DNA! Because of this mixing, any specific piece of DNA has a limited time, or 'half-life,' on a chromosome. Eventually, it will be separated from its neighboring pieces. Richard Dawkins, a famous scientist, explains that a gene isn't just a fixed piece of DNA. Instead, it's any part of the chromosome that can last long enough to be important for natural selection, which is how traits get passed down through generations. Shorter pieces of DNA are more likely to stay together during this mixing process than longer pieces. So, in Dawkins's view, a gene is usually a small stretch of DNA that can survive many of these mixing events. This is why we focus on genes instead of entire chromosomes when we talk about natural selection. Chromosomes get shuffled every generation, like a deck of cards, but a successful gene can stick around for millions of years. It can make copies of itself that spread across many different living things. Dawkins calls the gene an 'immortal coil.' This means that while a single gene isn't immortal on its own, it can live on forever through many copies that are passed down through generations. This idea helps us understand how traits and characteristics can persist in nature, shaping the living world around us. Genes are like tiny time capsules of information that can travel through time, helping to create the diversity of life we see today. So, when we think about genes, we are really thinking about the building blocks of life that connect all living things across time and space, showing us how interconnected we all are in the grand story of evolution.\nContext recap: A chromosome is like a long, twisty ladder made of DNA. When living things reproduce, this ladder gets mixed up in a fun way called crossing-over. Imagine two friends swapping pieces of their favorite stickers; that's similar to what happens with DNA! Because of this mixing, any specific piece of DNA has a limited time, or 'half-life,' on a chromosome.\nWhy this matters: What Exactly Is a Gene? The Immortal Coil helps learners in Science connect ideas from The Selfish Gene to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
